            <FONT color=3D#7f0000 size=3D+2>The Playing Field</FONT>
            <P>
            <P>The layout of the contest table is shown in Figures 1 and =
2. All=20
            measurements are guaranteed to be accurate to within 1/4 =
inches of=20
            the actual dimensions, though the only official measurements =
are=20
            those of the actual tables. The tables may also have seams, =
where=20
            sections of the table physically meet. Make sure your robot =
is=20
            capable of facing the imperfections of the board.</P>
            <CENTER>
            <TABLE cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D10 border=3D0>
              <TBODY>
              <TR>
                <TD><IMG src=3D""></TD></TR>
              <TR>
                <TD>
                  <CENTER><FONT size=3D-1><B>Figure=20
              1</B></FONT></CENTER></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></CENTER>
            <P>The surface base has a wall which runs around its =
perimeter. The=20
            board is divided into three regions---a white side on the =
right, a=20
            black side on the left, and a central strip. On either side =
of the=20
            central strip are troughs. In the middle of the central =
strip lies a=20
            square platform.</P>
            <P>The robots begin on either side of the platform on the =
central=20
            strip. The patterns on the central strip assist the robot in =

            determining which side it is on.</P>
            <P>The balls located at various points on the table are 4 =
inches in=20
            diameter and consist of dense plastic.</P>
            <P>One feature of the table that is not shown in the =
diagrams is a=20
            device that drops two more balls throughout the length of =
the match.=20
            At 20 seconds and again at 40 seconds into the round, if the =
central=20
            ball has been disturbed, another ball will be released from =
above=20
            onto the platform.</P><FONT color=3D#7f0000 =
size=3D+2>Scoring</FONT>
            <P>
            <UL>
              <LI>Each match lasts 60 seconds, during which time the =
robots=20
              attempt to score points. When time has expired, the robot =
with the=20
              most points wins.=20
              <LI>No human intervention is allowed during the match.=20
              <LI>Robots must conform to all requirements listed in the =
course=20
              notes. </LI></UL>
            <P>The score that each robot receives is determined by the =
final=20
            state of the contest table after the match has been played. =
The=20
            robot that has the most balls on its side wins the match. =
Balls left=20
            in the central strip do not count toward the score of either =
robot,=20
            regardless of the color of the table beneath them.</P>
            <P>In the case that there is a tie, robots which at any =
point did=20
            something during the match that directly improved their =
score=20
            instead of preventing the opposing robot from scoring =
receive a win,=20
            and those that did not receive a loss. Thus, in a tied =
situation, a=20
            double-win, double-loss, and a single win are all possible=20
            outcomes.</P><!-- END OF DOCUMENT --->
